WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.780 --> 00:00:04.730
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:23.040 --> 00:00:26.450
&gt;&gt; Bill Mesler: -- and I'm going
to be the commentator for today.

00:00:26.450 --> 00:00:31.280
And I call this the nepotism
section because we're going to hear

00:00:31.280 --> 00:00:37.110
from everybody who's ever held
Nathaniel's job before him.

00:00:37.110 --> 00:00:39.670
You're in for a treat today.

00:00:39.670 --> 00:00:45.530
But seriously, we're going to hear
from two wonderful astrobiologists.

00:00:45.530 --> 00:00:52.280
And the first is David Grinspoon
who is the Senior Scientist

00:00:52.280 --> 00:00:56.470
at the Planetary Science
Institute and a tremendous writer.

00:00:56.470 --> 00:01:00.860
A lot of you would've been familiar
with his book, "Lonely Planets,

00:01:00.860 --> 00:01:03.560
The Natural Philosophy
of Alien Life",

00:01:03.560 --> 00:01:10.390
which won the PEN Award
for Research Nonfiction.

00:01:10.390 --> 00:01:14.860 position:56%
And he's also-- he has a new book
coming out in December called "Earth

00:01:14.860 --> 00:01:18.430
in Human Hands" and be
sure you all buy that,

00:01:18.430 --> 00:01:21.790
put that on your Amazon wish list.

00:01:21.790 --> 00:01:25.230
I'm really excited to hear
David speak because I remember

00:01:25.230 --> 00:01:28.900
as a young boy, reading Cosmo--

00:01:28.900 --> 00:01:32.880
"Cosmos" by Carl Sagan,
the illustrated version.

00:01:32.880 --> 00:01:36.450
And the one thing that always stuck
in my head were those pictures

00:01:36.450 --> 00:01:41.990
of different forms of life that
could be found in the universe,

00:01:41.990 --> 00:01:45.980
the hypothetical forms of life.

00:01:45.980 --> 00:01:50.200
So, I think astrobiologist
have always been confronted

00:01:50.200 --> 00:01:53.730
with that question, what is
life, when they begin to think

00:01:53.730 --> 00:01:59.260
about what life could possibly be
like outside of our own planet.

00:01:59.260 --> 00:02:03.480
And for most of us, I think,
we would answer that question

00:02:03.480 --> 00:02:07.540
by saying what the
judge once famously said

00:02:07.540 --> 00:02:11.700
about pornography that, "I
don't know how to define it

00:02:11.700 --> 00:02:14.350
but I know it when I see it."

00:02:14.350 --> 00:02:17.990
But I think an astrobiologist
would say that they would--

00:02:17.990 --> 00:02:20.580
we might actually not be
able to use that definition.

00:02:20.580 --> 00:02:22.600 position:56%
We might not know it when we see it.

00:02:22.600 --> 00:02:28.150
It could be so different
that it makes the depictions

00:02:28.150 --> 00:02:31.370
of hypothetical life that
Sagan once put forward,

00:02:31.370 --> 00:02:34.440
look rather mundane
and quite like our own.

00:02:34.440 --> 00:02:38.890
And I think David is going
to talk about some scenarios

00:02:38.890 --> 00:02:43.410
in which life could
exist in ways that, well,

00:02:43.410 --> 00:02:47.980
we might not have even defined
it as life in ages past.

00:02:47.980 --> 00:02:50.760
So, now I hand it over.

00:02:55.970 --> 00:03:00.460 position:56%
&gt;&gt; David Grinspoon: All right, thank
you very much Bill and thank you all

00:03:00.460 --> 00:03:02.060
for making it back from lunch.

00:03:02.060 --> 00:03:05.110
I'll try to keep you
awake while you digest.

00:03:05.110 --> 00:03:08.410
And I just want to start
by saying it's a thrill

00:03:08.410 --> 00:03:11.030 position:56%
to be back here at the Kluge Center.

00:03:11.030 --> 00:03:17.180
What a wonderful palace of
scholarly wonder this is

00:03:17.180 --> 00:03:20.260
and my experience here was great.

00:03:20.260 --> 00:03:23.700
I'd like to think that it's
not just nepotism but heritage

00:03:23.700 --> 00:03:28.630
that is responsible for the
inclusion of the past chairs.

00:03:28.630 --> 00:03:31.070
And who knows, in 20 years,
it might be pretty crowded

00:03:31.070 --> 00:03:34.510
if there's a tradition here
of inviting them all back.

00:03:34.510 --> 00:03:42.620
I'm here I think to represent
the astro part of astrobiology.

00:03:42.620 --> 00:03:45.420
We've heard a lot of
bio and a lot of chem,

00:03:45.420 --> 00:03:52.660 position:56%
and I'm actually not someone the
traditional picture of an astronomer

00:03:52.660 --> 00:03:55.000
that goes to a lonely called
mountain top and looks

00:03:55.000 --> 00:04:00.270
through telescopes to try to figure
what's happening on distant orbs.

00:04:00.270 --> 00:04:05.350
But I do what I do as I work
with teams that build spacecraft

00:04:05.350 --> 00:04:07.750
and send them to other
planets and try to figure

00:04:07.750 --> 00:04:12.160
out what the environments and the
histories of those planets are,

00:04:12.160 --> 00:04:15.400
with the focus on the
question of habitability,

00:04:15.400 --> 00:04:20.950
where might there be good places
for life elsewhere in the universe.

00:04:20.950 --> 00:04:22.300
Which begs a lot of questions,

00:04:22.300 --> 00:04:25.770
some of the questions we've been
grappling with so far today,

00:04:25.770 --> 00:04:31.600
such as, as was mentioned in
that wonderful introduction,

00:04:31.600 --> 00:04:34.020
what do we mean when we say life?

00:04:34.020 --> 00:04:38.440
We maybe will know it when we
see it but is that good enough.

00:04:38.440 --> 00:04:42.940
Now, as an astrobiologist,
of course,

00:04:42.940 --> 00:04:46.640
what I really want is what
Spock has here, a tricorder,

00:04:46.640 --> 00:04:51.640
so I could just point it at a
planet or a potential life form

00:04:51.640 --> 00:04:54.110
and say, "It's alive, Jim.

00:04:54.110 --> 00:04:55.750
Or, it's dead, Jim.

00:04:55.750 --> 00:04:59.060 position:56%
I'm not getting life form readings."

00:04:59.060 --> 00:05:00.360
Is this thing working?

00:05:00.360 --> 00:05:06.140
But we don't have one of those
yet and it's hard to even imagine

00:05:06.140 --> 00:05:08.660
that we will have one of those
someday but maybe that's just

00:05:08.660 --> 00:05:12.750
because our science of
astrobiology is in its infancy.

00:05:12.750 --> 00:05:17.360
We are in the pre-discovery,
the pre-contact phase.

00:05:17.360 --> 00:05:21.710
Maybe we'll always be in that phase
but obviously if we're ever not,

00:05:21.710 --> 00:05:23.750
then our science will
be very different,

00:05:23.750 --> 00:05:25.840
the way we approach
questions like this.

00:05:25.840 --> 00:05:29.580
But as it is now, we
have a real paradox

00:05:29.580 --> 00:05:30.880
with regard to this question.

00:05:30.880 --> 00:05:34.080
I'm not going to go into detail
on what is life because I think,

00:05:34.080 --> 00:05:37.670
actually, Steve-- Steven Dick
who follows me is going to talk

00:05:37.670 --> 00:05:40.040
about this a little bit
more but I do want to point

00:05:40.040 --> 00:05:42.920
out because it's relevant
to what I'm going to talk

00:05:42.920 --> 00:05:45.640
about for a few minutes now
that which reminds me I need

00:05:45.640 --> 00:05:50.230
to start my little timer here
because there isn't one otherwise.

00:05:50.230 --> 00:05:51.530
Excellent.

00:05:51.530 --> 00:05:58.050 position:56%
I want to point out that the paradox
at the heart of this question

00:05:58.050 --> 00:06:02.690
for scientists and scholars
and just conscious beings

00:06:02.690 --> 00:06:06.850 position:56%
in this pre-contact, pre-discovery
phase, which is that we're searching

00:06:06.850 --> 00:06:09.390
for something that we
can't really define.

00:06:09.390 --> 00:06:12.840
How do we define something when
we only have one example of it?

00:06:12.840 --> 00:06:17.060 position:56%
That's not really a very
scientifically credible thing to do.

00:06:17.060 --> 00:06:19.480
If you're going to put
something in a classification

00:06:19.480 --> 00:06:22.490 position:56%
and say what its properties are then
hopefully you have multiple examples

00:06:22.490 --> 00:06:23.790
of it.

00:06:23.790 --> 00:06:25.090
Well, maybe we will someday.

00:06:25.090 --> 00:06:29.000
But as of now, we're searching
for it and when we find it,

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:31.740
we'll be able to define
it much better.

00:06:31.740 --> 00:06:33.870
But that's kind of weird,
searching for something

00:06:33.870 --> 00:06:37.180
that you can't say what
it is until you find it.

00:06:37.180 --> 00:06:40.960
So there is a little bit of a
paradox here and we grasp at things

00:06:40.960 --> 00:06:42.530
like we'll know it when we see it.

00:06:42.530 --> 00:06:44.030
But we're not completely stuck.

00:06:44.030 --> 00:06:45.850
There are useful things we can do.

00:06:45.850 --> 00:06:49.600
For example, we can
talk about searching

00:06:49.600 --> 00:06:52.140
for habitable conditions elsewhere.

00:06:52.140 --> 00:06:57.950
We can't say exactly in an ironclad
way perhaps exactly what life is,

00:06:57.950 --> 00:07:02.890
but we can give our
sense of what it needs.

00:07:04.290 --> 00:07:09.010
It seems like needing an energy
source is pretty safe, What--

00:07:09.010 --> 00:07:14.080
however you define life, it's going
to have to eat or consume something

00:07:14.080 --> 00:07:18.920
because if it's not doing
that, if it's not using energy

00:07:18.920 --> 00:07:22.090
and metabolizing then, you know,
what good is it as a life form.

00:07:22.090 --> 00:07:23.390
I don't know.

00:07:23.390 --> 00:07:24.690
I think that's pretty
safe that it needs energy.

00:07:24.690 --> 00:07:27.370
And then you get more
towards life as we know it.

00:07:27.370 --> 00:07:31.010
It probably needs some liquid
medium, maybe it needs water, OK,

00:07:31.010 --> 00:07:33.520
we're narrowing our
range of assumptions

00:07:33.520 --> 00:07:35.830
but it still gives
us something concrete

00:07:35.830 --> 00:07:38.180
and reasonable to search for.

00:07:38.180 --> 00:07:42.710
So, the conditions of life is
something we can try to define

00:07:42.710 --> 00:07:45.130
and search for even if we
don't quite know what it is.

00:07:45.130 --> 00:07:49.440
We can also look for what
Spock would call life signs.

00:07:49.440 --> 00:07:55.100
But that is life-- again, whatever
it is, it must be something

00:07:55.100 --> 00:07:57.550
that somehow perturbs
its environment.

00:07:57.550 --> 00:08:01.620
And there are more specific ideas
about this, not to get way into it,

00:08:01.620 --> 00:08:05.840
but the idea of chemical
disequilibrium

00:08:05.840 --> 00:08:09.140
that life is something that messes

00:08:09.140 --> 00:08:11.990
with the chemical balance
of its home planet.

00:08:11.990 --> 00:08:14.210
Certainly, Earth, the
one planet we know

00:08:14.210 --> 00:08:18.820
of with life is flagrantly
disturbed by the presence of life

00:08:18.820 --> 00:08:22.910
so that the atmosphere has
a composition that you--

00:08:22.910 --> 00:08:24.410
as far as we could tell, I mean,

00:08:24.410 --> 00:08:27.500
I'd put money on this even
while admittedly we're

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:29.440
in the pre-contact phase,
we don't know anything.

00:08:29.440 --> 00:08:35.440
I'd put money on that we will never
find a planet with an atmosphere

00:08:35.440 --> 00:08:39.440
as weird as Earth's
that doesn't have life.

00:08:39.440 --> 00:08:42.780
That's a life sign, an
atmosphere with mixes of chemicals

00:08:42.780 --> 00:08:47.570
that should not be there to
any other reasonable process.

00:08:47.570 --> 00:08:50.670
So, we can talk about life signs.

00:08:50.670 --> 00:08:54.150
And then-- And this is something
I'm barely going to scurred

00:08:54.150 --> 00:09:00.490
on in this talk but certainly if
there was an alien species looking

00:09:00.490 --> 00:09:05.530
at our planet, they would notice
also something else is happening

00:09:05.530 --> 00:09:06.830
to our planet.

00:09:06.830 --> 00:09:08.630
We can search for signs
of intelligent life.

00:09:08.630 --> 00:09:10.530
And that's another
thing I put in quotes

00:09:10.530 --> 00:09:12.560
because do we really
know what we're talking

00:09:12.560 --> 00:09:13.970
about when we use those words?

00:09:13.970 --> 00:09:16.220
It's interesting question.

00:09:16.220 --> 00:09:20.070
But that's certainly something
I think in this whole spectrum

00:09:20.070 --> 00:09:23.280
of things that we might find
elsewhere that betray the presence

00:09:23.280 --> 00:09:26.800
of organisms we shouldn't
completely ignore.

00:09:26.800 --> 00:09:33.780
So, there is another paradox,
couple of paradoxes we encounter

00:09:33.780 --> 00:09:37.050
with this question, and that
is when we go toward scales

00:09:37.050 --> 00:09:40.330
that are very small or very large.

00:09:40.330 --> 00:09:44.910
We can come up with
reasonable definitions of life

00:09:44.910 --> 00:09:48.250
but there's a strange
thing about life

00:09:48.250 --> 00:09:50.340
when you go to different scales.

00:09:50.340 --> 00:09:52.990
For instance, in this
graphic I've shown here.

00:09:52.990 --> 00:09:57.380
This human being, I think we
would all agree, is alive.

00:09:57.380 --> 00:10:01.040
It's composed of cells that I
think we would all agree are alive.

00:10:01.040 --> 00:10:04.540
They're very similar
to living organisms

00:10:04.540 --> 00:10:06.900 position:56%
that aren't part of large organisms.

00:10:06.900 --> 00:10:11.440
Those cells are composed
of molecules.

00:10:11.440 --> 00:10:14.240
Most molecules probably
aren't really alive and

00:10:14.240 --> 00:10:20.000
yet this DNA molecule, you might
be able to argue, is alive and

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:24.390
yet it's composed of atoms
that aren't, I would say.

00:10:24.390 --> 00:10:30.980
Now, this paradox is often leads us
to the strange case of the viruses,

00:10:30.980 --> 00:10:34.020
which a lot of people would say a
virus is not alive even though it

00:10:34.020 --> 00:10:36.370
has a lot of the properties
of a living organism

00:10:36.370 --> 00:10:42.400
because it cannot exist without
hijacking a larger living system.

00:10:42.400 --> 00:10:44.730
But if you're going to
say that then you would--

00:10:44.730 --> 00:10:48.030
I would submit, I have to
say human being is not alive

00:10:48.030 --> 00:10:51.450
because we cannot exist
without a larger system

00:10:51.450 --> 00:10:52.760
that we completely depend on.

00:10:52.760 --> 00:10:56.950
Put a human being naked on the
moon and see how long they survive.

00:10:56.950 --> 00:11:00.280
So, there's just some kind
of fun paradox as you get to.

00:11:00.280 --> 00:11:03.650
Now, that's at the small scale,
what about at the larger scale?

00:11:03.650 --> 00:11:07.960
We've been talking about the
origin of living organisms

00:11:07.960 --> 00:11:11.550
but there are properties of
living systems that are larger

00:11:11.550 --> 00:11:13.710
than organisms and there
are some ideas about this.

00:11:13.710 --> 00:11:17.500
There's living systems
theory and Harold Morowitz

00:11:17.500 --> 00:11:20.020
in the early '80s wrote
some interesting papers

00:11:20.020 --> 00:11:23.250
about what he called
the-- what did he call it?

00:11:23.250 --> 00:11:26.830
Basically the biological
properties of ecosystems that--

00:11:26.830 --> 00:11:30.760
where he submitted that
life might be better defined

00:11:30.760 --> 00:11:34.800
on that level rather than on
the individual organism level.

00:11:34.800 --> 00:11:38.380
And this-- then goes all the
way up to what you've heard

00:11:38.380 --> 00:11:43.010
of as the Gaia hypothesis, a much
abused and much maligned idea,

00:11:43.010 --> 00:11:46.840
which I think is also
very profoundly important,

00:11:46.840 --> 00:11:51.820
the idea that a planetary biosphere
has some properties similar

00:11:51.820 --> 00:11:55.160
to those of living systems.

00:11:55.160 --> 00:11:58.840
So in this graphic, you
see this sort of bug

00:11:58.840 --> 00:12:00.460
where they're obviously
living organisms,

00:12:00.460 --> 00:12:02.510
these birds and fish and things.

00:12:02.510 --> 00:12:06.740
But then there are these-- for
instance, the dead log is dead

00:12:06.740 --> 00:12:10.110
but the-- some of these other
organisms are completely dependent

00:12:10.110 --> 00:12:11.410
upon it for their life.

00:12:11.410 --> 00:12:16.490
So in some larger sense,
that decaying log is part

00:12:16.490 --> 00:12:21.610
of this living entity,
this biosphere of the bug.

00:12:21.610 --> 00:12:25.440
And, of course, you have the
case of the coral reefs where the

00:12:25.440 --> 00:12:30.470
"dead parts" form the
skeletal structure that the

00:12:30.470 --> 00:12:32.870
"living parts" are
completely dependent upon,

00:12:32.870 --> 00:12:35.150
and so the whole thing
has a life fit

00:12:35.150 --> 00:12:36.840
in a sense is larger
than the organisms.

00:12:36.840 --> 00:12:38.350
And then you take that
to the larger scale,

00:12:38.350 --> 00:12:45.370
this picture on the lower right,
reefs completely remake landscapes.

00:12:45.370 --> 00:12:50.020
And so there's the boundary
between living and dead even

00:12:50.020 --> 00:12:55.630
on that geographic landscape
scale is not completely clear.

00:12:55.630 --> 00:12:58.460
And then you take that all the
way up to the planetary level,

00:12:58.460 --> 00:13:00.780
and again, you're left
with this Gaia picture.

00:13:00.780 --> 00:13:03.620
And the Gaia hypothesis, by the
way, as I said, it's been maligned

00:13:03.620 --> 00:13:06.480
as the Earth is alive, the Earth
is a living organism in a sort

00:13:06.480 --> 00:13:10.100
of new edgy way, which is nice
and poetic, I kind of like it.

00:13:10.100 --> 00:13:13.340
But there's actually a more
scientifically useful way

00:13:13.340 --> 00:13:18.320
of thinking about it which is
that the totality of the "living"

00:13:18.320 --> 00:13:24.670
and "nonliving" parts of the
Earth function in a way so as

00:13:24.670 --> 00:13:30.750 position:56%
to achieve homeostasis that tend to
emphasize certain negative feedbacks

00:13:30.750 --> 00:13:37.450
that keep the whole ball as it
were rolling in a way that keeps it

00:13:37.450 --> 00:13:40.610
in that range of physical
conditions that are conducive

00:13:40.610 --> 00:13:43.870
to the furtherance of life,
just as in your own body,

00:13:43.870 --> 00:13:46.580
there's homeostasis going in
with your temperature and the pH

00:13:46.580 --> 00:13:48.360
of your blood and all these things.

00:13:48.360 --> 00:13:51.150
And it gives us a slightly
different picture of evolution.

00:13:51.150 --> 00:13:54.960
It's actually a modification of
Darwinism because you realize

00:13:54.960 --> 00:13:58.000
that it's not the case where
the environment is just changing

00:13:58.000 --> 00:13:59.750
and life is just adapting to it.

00:13:59.750 --> 00:14:02.930
But on a planetary scale,
life changes the environment

00:14:02.930 --> 00:14:06.130
and so therefore it's a feedback
and a dance between the two

00:14:06.130 --> 00:14:09.270
that can lead a planet to a very
different state than it would be

00:14:09.270 --> 00:14:13.640
if it were not, in a certain
sense, taken over by life.

00:14:13.640 --> 00:14:18.390
And as my colleague,
Colin Goldblatt put this,

00:14:18.390 --> 00:14:22.190
the defining characteristic of
Earth is planetary scale life

00:14:22.190 --> 00:14:24.650
and Earth teaches us
that habitability

00:14:24.650 --> 00:14:28.620
and inhabitants are inseparable.

00:14:28.620 --> 00:14:32.600 position:56%
In other words, if you compare Earth
to other planets, which I'm going

00:14:32.600 --> 00:14:38.520 position:56%
to do a little bit more in a minute,
it jumps out at you how the life

00:14:38.520 --> 00:14:43.090
of Earth dominate so many of
its physical characteristic,

00:14:43.090 --> 00:14:46.200
not just the composition of
the atmospheres I mentioned

00:14:46.200 --> 00:14:50.820
but the mineral balance
of the planet that about--

00:14:50.820 --> 00:14:53.860
more than half of the
minerals on Earth exist

00:14:53.860 --> 00:14:56.710
because of living systems,
the composition

00:14:56.710 --> 00:14:58.980
of the ocean, the climate.

00:14:58.980 --> 00:15:03.290
Even now, some people think the
composition of Earth's interior,

00:15:03.290 --> 00:15:05.680
which affects the material
properties and convection

00:15:05.680 --> 00:15:09.690
of the planet more
speculatively and the heat flow

00:15:09.690 --> 00:15:12.220
of the planet are influenced by

00:15:12.220 --> 00:15:15.710
and potentially controlled
to some extent by life.

00:15:15.710 --> 00:15:18.500
So Earth is a planet
where habitability

00:15:18.500 --> 00:15:21.700
and inhabitants have
become inseparable.

00:15:21.700 --> 00:15:23.980
And we're not really sure
how far that goes back.

00:15:23.980 --> 00:15:25.600
But when we compare
Earth to the neighbors,

00:15:25.600 --> 00:15:28.600
Venus and Mars, it's
a stark difference.

00:15:28.600 --> 00:15:33.520
Now, one other way to think about
life, I just want to mention.

00:15:33.520 --> 00:15:38.100
This comes from the field of
non-equilibrium thermodynamics

00:15:38.100 --> 00:15:40.940
and there's something called
a dissipative structure

00:15:40.940 --> 00:15:44.210
that you've all seen because
you've seen "Dust Devils"

00:15:44.210 --> 00:15:46.900
and at least films of tornados,

00:15:46.900 --> 00:15:49.310
hopefully you've not
seen one really up close.

00:15:49.310 --> 00:15:54.150
But you've also seen whirlpools
and vortices and not just on Earth.

00:15:54.150 --> 00:15:59.340
On the upper right here, this
is on Venus, this polar vortex.

00:15:59.340 --> 00:16:03.700
And a dissipate structure is a
structure that arises spontaneously

00:16:03.700 --> 00:16:08.020
when you have the right kind
of flow of matter and energy

00:16:08.020 --> 00:16:12.520
and matter organizes itself in
a way to facilitate that flow.

00:16:12.520 --> 00:16:16.170
It's sort of spontaneous
order that arises from flow.

00:16:16.170 --> 00:16:20.550
And you look at this
standing waves and this stream

00:16:20.550 --> 00:16:24.880
on the bottom graphic here
and you can, if you want,

00:16:24.880 --> 00:16:28.610
relate that to yourself
and think what am I?

00:16:28.610 --> 00:16:34.180
Am I the atoms and molecules
that right now are part of me

00:16:34.180 --> 00:16:36.110
but they're not going to
be part of me in the future

00:16:36.110 --> 00:16:40.200
and they weren't always part
of me and yet I'm still me.

00:16:40.200 --> 00:16:46.500
So, there's a sense in which that a
standing wave, which is a structure

00:16:46.500 --> 00:16:49.880
that persists even as the
matter flows through it,

00:16:49.880 --> 00:16:53.880
is an interesting model
for what a life form is.

00:16:53.880 --> 00:16:59.320
And if you think of life as that,
as something that arises from flows

00:16:59.320 --> 00:17:02.790
of matter and energy,
structures that evolve from that,

00:17:02.790 --> 00:17:06.160
then again you can think of
the Earth and its biosphere

00:17:06.160 --> 00:17:11.310
as the most complex dissipative
structure that we know.

00:17:11.310 --> 00:17:18.320
And another example
of such a structure

00:17:18.320 --> 00:17:20.880 position:56%
that you're familiar with is a fire.

00:17:20.880 --> 00:17:24.800 position:56%
And this also has another--
captures another quality that I want

00:17:24.800 --> 00:17:26.490
to mention because I think
it might be important

00:17:26.490 --> 00:17:29.510
in how we think about
life on planets.

00:17:29.510 --> 00:17:33.870
And that is-- think about when you
build a campfire and you're trying

00:17:33.870 --> 00:17:38.470 position:56%
to get it started, and at first it's
just sparks and it's really hard

00:17:38.470 --> 00:17:40.530
to get it going, and
you have to keep--

00:17:40.530 --> 00:17:42.630
stay there and keep
blowing on it and it does--

00:17:42.630 --> 00:17:44.710
you know, you got sparks
and you've got your fuel

00:17:44.710 --> 00:17:47.770
but it's quite disorganized
and it's really-- it's a pain.

00:17:47.770 --> 00:17:50.440
But then you get it to a
point where it's going enough

00:17:50.440 --> 00:17:53.680
and the coals are hot and it's
creating its own convection pattern

00:17:53.680 --> 00:17:57.440
by sucking in air and the hot air
rising and then it's fueling itself

00:17:57.440 --> 00:18:00.760
by pulling in oxygen and then
it becomes self-sustaining,

00:18:00.760 --> 00:18:04.330
and it's a self-sustaining
dissipative structure

00:18:04.330 --> 00:18:07.260
which is pulling in its own
fuel and taking advantage

00:18:07.260 --> 00:18:11.960
of the cyclic motion of
nutrients through itself.

00:18:11.960 --> 00:18:15.800
And it's possible that that's
what a global biosphere is.

00:18:15.800 --> 00:18:19.290
And that I want to make the
distinction between the origin

00:18:19.290 --> 00:18:23.240
of life that we've been discussing
which is, it seems to be discussed

00:18:23.240 --> 00:18:27.440 position:56%
as a local phenomenon, something
that happens one place or one region

00:18:27.440 --> 00:18:31.460
but doesn't simultaneously
happen all around the planet.

00:18:31.460 --> 00:18:38.330 position:56%
And the origin of a global biosphere
that is a self-sustaining part

00:18:38.330 --> 00:18:42.500
of the way a planet is operating,
which is clearly what we have here.

00:18:42.500 --> 00:18:45.240
And when we look around
at other planets,

00:18:45.240 --> 00:18:46.980
which is what I spend
my time doing and think

00:18:46.980 --> 00:18:50.070 position:56%
of the properties we're looking for,
we're really looking for the latter.

00:18:50.070 --> 00:18:53.280
I think we're looking-- it's going
to be easier to find biospheres

00:18:53.280 --> 00:18:56.810
or evidence of biospheres than
organisms or evidence probably

00:18:56.810 --> 00:19:00.980
of organisms, although that
obviously depends on the case.

00:19:00.980 --> 00:19:05.440 position:56%
And it may be that life goes through
a stage initially where the origin

00:19:05.440 --> 00:19:08.800
of life, that's like those
sparks that may fizzle

00:19:08.800 --> 00:19:13.470
and die unless they're fed by
the right kind of cyclic flows.

00:19:13.470 --> 00:19:16.360
But life can get to a point in
its existence on the planet that's

00:19:16.360 --> 00:19:18.340
like that self-sustaining fire.

00:19:18.340 --> 00:19:21.470 position:56%
And I'm interested in that potential
difference between the origin

00:19:21.470 --> 00:19:27.720
of life, meaning there's some
physical system that is behaving

00:19:27.720 --> 00:19:30.560
like an organism in the ways we've
been discussing and the origin

00:19:30.560 --> 00:19:35.200
of a global biosphere that might be
a property that a planet takes on.

00:19:35.200 --> 00:19:37.550
In other words, in a sense,
maybe life is not just something

00:19:37.550 --> 00:19:41.090
that happens on a planet but
something that happens to a planet

00:19:41.090 --> 00:19:43.160
or something that a planet becomes.

00:19:43.160 --> 00:19:49.370
So, this leads me to the musical
question, can a planet be alive?

00:19:49.370 --> 00:19:53.250
And it's something I've
thought about a lot especially

00:19:53.250 --> 00:19:55.920
with reference to comparative
planetology

00:19:55.920 --> 00:19:58.750
which is really my day job.

00:19:58.750 --> 00:20:05.000
And there's a growing field
among those who do study planets,

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:08.640
where what we really are interested
in is comparing the life stories

00:20:08.640 --> 00:20:11.490
and environments of planets
to try to understand them,

00:20:11.490 --> 00:20:17.140
not just as points in
time but as pathways,

00:20:17.140 --> 00:20:21.990
as stories that collectively
illustrate properties

00:20:21.990 --> 00:20:23.610
about what can happen to planets.

00:20:23.610 --> 00:20:25.790
And one thing that can
happen to planets clearly

00:20:25.790 --> 00:20:28.230
because it has here
is becoming alive.

00:20:28.230 --> 00:20:34.870
So, how does this question of
whether a planet can be alive?

00:20:34.870 --> 00:20:38.290
How is that illustrated or
what light can we shed on that

00:20:38.290 --> 00:20:40.390
by looking around at the neighbors?

00:20:40.390 --> 00:20:44.030
Well, we look at Mars
and never really--

00:20:44.030 --> 00:20:48.730
ever since 1971, we've known
that Mars is a place that seems

00:20:48.730 --> 00:20:50.860
to have been much more Earth-like.

00:20:50.860 --> 00:20:54.300
I say '71 because that's when
Mariner 9, the first orbiter got

00:20:54.300 --> 00:20:57.980
to Mars and really started and we
saw that it was the older parts

00:20:57.980 --> 00:21:00.590
of Mars are covered
by dried up riverbeds.

00:21:00.590 --> 00:21:05.850
And as we've explored Mars in depth
since then, we've learned much more

00:21:05.850 --> 00:21:09.700 position:56%
that indicates that Mars, when it
was young, was much more Earth-like.

00:21:09.700 --> 00:21:14.230
And now, we're-- we have this
wonderful rover curiosity that's

00:21:14.230 --> 00:21:18.990 position:56%
slowly crawling across this lakebed,
it turns out it is a lakebed

00:21:18.990 --> 00:21:22.390
as we thought from orbit of Gale
crater and starting to climb

00:21:22.390 --> 00:21:25.800
up this mountain, Mount Sharp
and finding copious evidence

00:21:25.800 --> 00:21:31.240
of a more watery, more wet,
more benign in terms of climate,

00:21:31.240 --> 00:21:34.970
more Earth-like path than--
and just one bit of evidence.

00:21:34.970 --> 00:21:39.000
You can see in this image
here, this rounded cobble,

00:21:39.000 --> 00:21:41.210
these are river rocks,
where you couldn't tell.

00:21:41.210 --> 00:21:43.680
But when you look at them up close
and you compare them to rocks

00:21:43.680 --> 00:21:46.820
on Earth, these are rock-- this
is a place where water has flown.

00:21:46.820 --> 00:21:49.020
And I won't go into
more detail about Mars.

00:21:49.020 --> 00:21:52.950
Obviously, one can talk a
lot about this but, you know,

00:21:52.950 --> 00:21:56.420
the punch line is that
Mars, when it was younger,

00:21:56.420 --> 00:21:58.490
was a more Earth-like place.

00:21:58.490 --> 00:22:04.320
And precisely those qualities
that we think would be conducive

00:22:04.320 --> 00:22:08.130
to an origin of life as we
are, you know, imperfectly

00:22:08.130 --> 00:22:12.980
but increasingly seem to understand
the requirements for that.

00:22:12.980 --> 00:22:14.680
And there are some
problems with Mars.

00:22:14.680 --> 00:22:17.950
The climate models don't quite work
to make it warm when it was young

00:22:17.950 --> 00:22:20.360
but the geology tells
us it was watery

00:22:20.360 --> 00:22:22.880
so there's still something
we're missing about Mars

00:22:22.880 --> 00:22:25.160
but things are pointing
in that direction.

00:22:25.160 --> 00:22:29.250
Now, when we go to the other
neighbor, Venus, as you know now,

00:22:29.250 --> 00:22:31.770
Venus is hell on the surface.

00:22:31.770 --> 00:22:34.320
It's far too hot for
our kind of life.

00:22:34.320 --> 00:22:35.930
There's almost no water.

00:22:35.930 --> 00:22:38.860
It's not a place you
would want to live today.

00:22:38.860 --> 00:22:44.630
But in the past, our understanding
of Venus is more clouded, you know,

00:22:44.630 --> 00:22:47.770
literally and metaphorically
than our understanding of Mars.

00:22:47.770 --> 00:22:51.720
But what we have learned
so far points us to Venus,

00:22:51.720 --> 00:22:55.420
being in the past, also a
much more Earth-like place.

00:22:55.420 --> 00:22:58.420
And we have some designs for new
missions which we're hoping to fly

00:22:58.420 --> 00:23:00.960
in the near future,
which are really designed

00:23:00.960 --> 00:23:02.740
to take the measurements
that'll help us pin

00:23:02.740 --> 00:23:04.760
down whether that's
really true about Venus.

00:23:04.760 --> 00:23:07.510
But as far as we can tell, if
I had to draw you a picture

00:23:07.510 --> 00:23:10.600
of the earliest environment
of Venus or not quite--

00:23:10.600 --> 00:23:15.710 position:56%
the second environment of Venus
after it was a fiery pit of impacts,

00:23:15.710 --> 00:23:17.010
as all the planet started out.

00:23:17.010 --> 00:23:19.930
But then once that
quieted down, I would say,

00:23:19.930 --> 00:23:21.750
it would be sort of
like this picture.

00:23:21.750 --> 00:23:24.150
And you notice this
picture is kind of murky

00:23:24.150 --> 00:23:25.760
because our understanding is murky.

00:23:25.760 --> 00:23:31.070
But basically, this is what Venus
and Mars probably both looked

00:23:31.070 --> 00:23:34.800
like around the time we think the
origin of life happened on Earth.

00:23:34.800 --> 00:23:38.120
They were water worlds and
they probably had black smokers

00:23:38.120 --> 00:23:41.340
and things like that because the
heat flow was much higher then

00:23:41.340 --> 00:23:46.920
and things point towards
origins that were conducive

00:23:46.920 --> 00:23:49.960
to life on these planets.

00:23:49.960 --> 00:23:55.280
And this makes me think that
the lesson, the punch line

00:23:55.280 --> 00:23:57.890
of comparative planetology
in our region of space

00:23:57.890 --> 00:24:00.680
and increasingly further a field is

00:24:00.680 --> 00:24:04.010
that rocky planets have similar
origins in early environments,

00:24:04.010 --> 00:24:09.640
that is not uncommon for rocky
planets to have wet condition,

00:24:09.640 --> 00:24:13.710
not just wet but in places
where there are chemical flows

00:24:13.710 --> 00:24:16.840
and interactions with
geothermal heat

00:24:16.840 --> 00:24:20.860
and they all certainly
had organic molecules

00:24:20.860 --> 00:24:22.160 position:56%
because we're learning more and more

00:24:22.160 --> 00:24:24.480
that organic molecules are
basically everywhere falling

00:24:24.480 --> 00:24:26.750
from the sky and being synthesized.

00:24:26.750 --> 00:24:31.930
And so, I would say that from what
we know about the origin of life

00:24:31.930 --> 00:24:35.550
and its requirements, which
as you heard, are, you know,

00:24:35.550 --> 00:24:37.370
still far from perfect knowledge.

00:24:37.370 --> 00:24:41.110 position:56%
But from what we know and from what
we know about the early environments

00:24:41.110 --> 00:24:45.850
of these planets, there should've
been life on all three of them.

00:24:45.850 --> 00:24:51.470
Not only do I say that because it
seems like conditions were right

00:24:51.470 --> 00:24:54.230
on those planets but even if
it was something more rare,

00:24:54.230 --> 00:24:55.530
another thing we've learned is

00:24:55.530 --> 00:24:57.760
that the planets were all
exchanging materials back then.

00:24:57.760 --> 00:25:01.310
There were bits getting blasted off
of one and landing on the other.

00:25:01.310 --> 00:25:05.560
And microbes being the
hardy beasts that they are,

00:25:05.560 --> 00:25:08.280
life would have been
transported from one to another.

00:25:08.280 --> 00:25:13.160
So even if origin of life
is rare, you might not need

00:25:13.160 --> 00:25:15.320
to have it indigenous to a planet.

00:25:15.320 --> 00:25:17.150
If it happened on one
of the neighbors,

00:25:17.150 --> 00:25:18.960
it could've easily spread.

00:25:18.960 --> 00:25:21.080
So, similar origins
on early environments

00:25:21.080 --> 00:25:26.000
and therefore what is rare
is not perhaps the conditions

00:25:26.000 --> 00:25:29.810
for the origin of life but the
persistence of the conditions

00:25:29.810 --> 00:25:33.130
to maintain life over
cosmological time scales.

00:25:33.130 --> 00:25:36.780
That is over billions of
years, the ages of planets.

00:25:36.780 --> 00:25:40.280
And that leads me back to
this question did the presence

00:25:40.280 --> 00:25:43.620
of a global biosphere on Earth
help with that persistence?

00:25:43.620 --> 00:25:46.050
So, maybe it's not-- we're
not just completely lucky.

00:25:46.050 --> 00:25:50.660
Maybe life itself had a hand
in keeping Earth habitable.

00:25:50.660 --> 00:25:53.000
Now, the very first
environment of all these planets,

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:54.970
as I mentioned, was hellacious.

00:25:54.970 --> 00:25:57.790
We know they started off very
violently with a lot of collisions.

00:25:57.790 --> 00:26:01.740
And this is the period of time
on Earth we call the Hadean,

00:26:01.740 --> 00:26:03.800
which literally means hellish.

00:26:03.800 --> 00:26:08.120
That was the first eon of
Earth history lasting up until

00:26:08.120 --> 00:26:09.850
about 4 billion years ago.

00:26:09.850 --> 00:26:13.520
And interestingly, I think
we can be pretty certain

00:26:13.520 --> 00:26:17.420
that the Hadean was not a phase
unique to Earth, that Venus

00:26:17.420 --> 00:26:22.540
and Mars had a Hadean around
the same time as Earth.

00:26:22.540 --> 00:26:24.500 position:56%
Now, did they also have an Archean ?

00:26:24.500 --> 00:26:26.140
That's a really interesting
question.

00:26:26.140 --> 00:26:30.470
So, here we have three
young terrestrial planets

00:26:30.470 --> 00:26:38.260
and then something happened to
the middle one, to lead it to--

00:26:38.260 --> 00:26:41.530
what we've been hearing about,
there was an origin of life

00:26:41.530 --> 00:26:46.490 position:56%
and I leave the details to the bio
and chemistry parts of astrobiology.

00:26:46.490 --> 00:26:49.190
But clearly it happened in one
place and I have question marks

00:26:49.190 --> 00:26:51.340
about whether it happened
in these other places.

00:26:51.340 --> 00:26:54.440
If it didn't, then I think we
have to figure out why not.

00:26:54.440 --> 00:26:59.130
But then, what I wonder is was
there another transition after that

00:26:59.130 --> 00:27:04.320
to a global biosphere
on Earth, where the--

00:27:04.320 --> 00:27:06.100
you could've have life
on all three planets

00:27:06.100 --> 00:27:09.080
but it could've only
persisted on the one planet

00:27:09.080 --> 00:27:12.700
where the geophysical conditions
were perhaps more friendly

00:27:12.700 --> 00:27:16.820
for that continued set of
flows of nutrients and energy

00:27:16.820 --> 00:27:19.890
on that stable surface environment
that allowed a global biosphere

00:27:19.890 --> 00:27:25.220
to develop and take over and
then maintain its own existence.

00:27:25.220 --> 00:27:30.000
Now, you've all seen the
geological time scale

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:33.620
where we have these different
ages and famously, you know,

00:27:33.620 --> 00:27:36.410
the Jurassic is famous
because it's a movie star.

00:27:36.410 --> 00:27:39.390
And after that, there's the
Cretaceous and the Tertiary

00:27:39.390 --> 00:27:42.590
and all these are or now,
it's actually the Paleocene

00:27:42.590 --> 00:27:44.940
and all these different ages.

00:27:44.940 --> 00:27:50.270
And over on the right side of this
chart are the little, you know,

00:27:50.270 --> 00:27:53.970 position:56%
I say little, they've lasts for, you
know, a few millions years, nothing.

00:27:53.970 --> 00:27:56.950
These are what we call the epochs.

00:27:56.950 --> 00:28:00.440
And the epochs are not major
events in the life of the Earth.

00:28:00.440 --> 00:28:03.290
They are important to the biota
who were alive at that time

00:28:03.290 --> 00:28:06.380
because they're often
marked by extinction events,

00:28:06.380 --> 00:28:09.200
climate changes, changes
in sea level.

00:28:09.200 --> 00:28:12.470
There fluctuations that
change what can leave, where.

00:28:12.470 --> 00:28:15.760
But they don't really
affect the planet that much.

00:28:15.760 --> 00:28:17.510
Far over on the left are the eons.

00:28:17.510 --> 00:28:19.580
There's only been four eons.

00:28:19.580 --> 00:28:22.310
And the eons are interesting
to me as an astrobiologist

00:28:22.310 --> 00:28:24.380
because I'm interested
in the relationship

00:28:24.380 --> 00:28:25.780
between life and a planet.

00:28:25.780 --> 00:28:28.940
And each of these eon
boundaries, I would suggest,

00:28:28.940 --> 00:28:33.160
is a time when the character of the
planet fundamentally changed and,

00:28:33.160 --> 00:28:35.050
in particular, the
relationship between life

00:28:35.050 --> 00:28:36.900
and the planet fundamentally
changed.

00:28:36.900 --> 00:28:40.640
The Hadean, it was dead
because it was just not a place

00:28:40.640 --> 00:28:44.180
where you would want to live
or anything probably could

00:28:44.180 --> 00:28:47.090
because it was-- there was
not a stable surface and now,

00:28:47.090 --> 00:28:52.750
you were getting-- my colleague,
Kevin Zahnle refers to the Hadean

00:28:52.750 --> 00:28:58.580
as an age of fire and brimstone
punctuated with blows to the head.

00:28:58.580 --> 00:29:00.290
So that's the Hadean.

00:29:00.290 --> 00:29:04.480
But the Archean is
roughly, and geologist

00:29:04.480 --> 00:29:06.990
and geochemist will throw things
at me, you know, because I'm going

00:29:06.990 --> 00:29:08.470
to make some crude statements.

00:29:08.470 --> 00:29:09.770
But that's basically the trend.

00:29:09.770 --> 00:29:12.150
The boundary between the Hadean
and the Archean is the origin

00:29:12.150 --> 00:29:16.230 position:56%
of life more or less 4 billion
years ago some people put it at 3.8.

00:29:16.230 --> 00:29:19.870
That's when life-- when
the planet came alive.

00:29:19.870 --> 00:29:23.090
Clearly, the other planets had a
Hadean, did they have an Archean?

00:29:23.090 --> 00:29:24.390
That's an interesting question.

00:29:24.390 --> 00:29:28.810
Now, I think the Proterozoic,
which is the next eon,

00:29:28.810 --> 00:29:32.690
is arguably the time when
life took over the planet.

00:29:32.690 --> 00:29:35.340 position:56%
It's when we have the rise of oxygen

00:29:35.340 --> 00:29:39.370
from the cyanobacteria
polluting the atmosphere

00:29:39.370 --> 00:29:40.700
with all this nasty oxygen.

00:29:40.700 --> 00:29:43.860
They were the original
bad actors who,

00:29:43.860 --> 00:29:45.800
in the search for a
new energy source,

00:29:45.800 --> 00:29:50.020
polluted the entire atmosphere and
collapsed the climate in, you know,

00:29:50.020 --> 00:29:53.180
and just for their
own selfish purposes.

00:29:53.180 --> 00:29:55.330
Anyway, so I think
the Proterozoic is

00:29:55.330 --> 00:29:58.710
when the life perhaps
took over the planet.

00:29:58.710 --> 00:30:03.020
The Phanerozoic which
started basically

00:30:03.020 --> 00:30:10.140
over 500 million years ago is
the time when life got complex,

00:30:10.140 --> 00:30:14.300
and animals and plants form and
life was not just multicellular

00:30:14.300 --> 00:30:18.290
and all the forms of life, the
macrolife we're familiar with

00:30:18.290 --> 00:30:19.720 position:56%
and the fossils we're familiar with.

00:30:19.720 --> 00:30:23.220
There was a seemingly
rather abrupt transition

00:30:23.220 --> 00:30:24.790
and that's what we
call the Phanerozoic.

00:30:24.790 --> 00:30:28.110
So each of these is sort of a
transition in the relationship

00:30:28.110 --> 00:30:29.410
between life in the planet.

00:30:29.410 --> 00:30:31.880
And as an astrobiologist, as I
said, I'm interested in these

00:30:31.880 --> 00:30:33.560
because I can imagine, you know,

00:30:33.560 --> 00:30:36.680
all these little changes
on the right side.

00:30:36.680 --> 00:30:39.140
These epochs are unique to Earth.

00:30:39.140 --> 00:30:41.780
They're Earth's random evolution.

00:30:41.780 --> 00:30:44.480 position:56%
But as you go to this left side this
major transitions, I would submit

00:30:44.480 --> 00:30:46.160
to you that each one
of these is something

00:30:46.160 --> 00:30:47.480
that astrobiologist could look

00:30:47.480 --> 00:30:51.420
for on other planet
that-- OK, OK, I hear you.

00:30:51.420 --> 00:30:54.690
That-- sorry, my phone is
telling me to hurry up.

00:30:54.690 --> 00:30:57.010
That-- It's probably good advice.

00:30:57.010 --> 00:30:59.990
That other planets
definitely had a Hadean.

00:30:59.990 --> 00:31:04.080
If they had an origin of life,
we could say they had an Archean.

00:31:04.080 --> 00:31:08.080
If life took over as it did on
Earth, that might be analogous

00:31:08.080 --> 00:31:11.320
to our Proterozoic and if
life became complex then

00:31:11.320 --> 00:31:12.680
that could be the Phanerozoic.

00:31:12.680 --> 00:31:14.720
So these are all things
that astrobiologist talk

00:31:14.720 --> 00:31:16.020
about looking for on other planets.

00:31:16.020 --> 00:31:19.530
And so I think these eons
map into possibilities

00:31:19.530 --> 00:31:22.390
for other planets whereas
the smaller boundaries,

00:31:22.390 --> 00:31:25.250
the epochs stuff are clearly
just part of the Earth's story.

00:31:25.250 --> 00:31:29.310
So, I want to just
mention one last transition

00:31:29.310 --> 00:31:32.570
which is something is happening
to Earth now that's new

00:31:32.570 --> 00:31:33.870
if you had been watching Earth

00:31:33.870 --> 00:31:38.080
over the eons or/and you're a
patient alien watching Earth

00:31:38.080 --> 00:31:39.380
from space.

00:31:39.380 --> 00:31:42.220
You would notice suddenly things
had change that Earth lit up

00:31:42.220 --> 00:31:45.860
and the atmosphere composition
and the ocean composition

00:31:45.860 --> 00:31:49.450
or the ocean acidity is changing,
the land surfaces are changing,

00:31:49.450 --> 00:31:51.880
these strange linear
clouds are striking

00:31:51.880 --> 00:31:53.780
through the oceans
and across the sky.

00:31:53.780 --> 00:31:56.920
There's something up on this
planet that it wasn't up before.

00:31:56.920 --> 00:32:02.110
And the nature of that transition
is basically what I was studying

00:32:02.110 --> 00:32:06.040
when I was here as the
astrobiology chair a few years ago,

00:32:06.040 --> 00:32:10.170 position:56%
and it's something that people had
been calling the Anthropocene epoch.

00:32:10.170 --> 00:32:15.080
But I want to submit to you
that maybe it's not an epoch,

00:32:15.080 --> 00:32:20.000
it might be an epoch boundary but
it might also be an eon boundary,

00:32:20.000 --> 00:32:21.400
one of these major changes.

00:32:21.400 --> 00:32:22.700
Why would I say that?

00:32:22.700 --> 00:32:26.710
I think it's a fundamental change
in the relationship between life

00:32:26.710 --> 00:32:34.220
and the planet because cognitive
processes, making things, tool use,

00:32:34.220 --> 00:32:37.960
are changing the planet
in profound ways.

00:32:37.960 --> 00:32:40.490
And life has changed the
planet many times in the past

00:32:40.490 --> 00:32:43.340
but cognitive processes being
involved in the functioning

00:32:43.340 --> 00:32:46.150
of the planet, that's
something new and very strange.

00:32:46.150 --> 00:32:50.400 position:56%
And if it persists, I think arguably
as significant even as the origin

00:32:50.400 --> 00:32:54.060
of life and therefore
could be an eon boundary.

00:32:54.060 --> 00:32:58.450
We won't know for hundreds
of millions of years this--

00:32:58.450 --> 00:33:01.630
my idea cannot be disproven
even by the remote,

00:33:01.630 --> 00:33:03.810
remote descendants
from-- of anyone alive now

00:33:03.810 --> 00:33:06.670
so I feel pretty confident
in making it.

00:33:06.670 --> 00:33:10.720 position:56%
But anyways, so here's dead planets,
here's planets with the origin

00:33:10.720 --> 00:33:13.120
