everything that's not alive.

00:44:08.420 --> 00:44:10.930
Somehow I don't think
that's really very helpful

00:44:10.930 --> 00:44:17.040
but the question is an old one,
it's contemplated by biologist

00:44:17.040 --> 00:44:23.290
and biochemist physicist like
Schrodinger over several centuries.

00:44:23.290 --> 00:44:28.400
That history reads like
a mirror of each period

00:44:28.400 --> 00:44:30.720
when the question was
asked as biologist try

00:44:30.720 --> 00:44:33.860
to determine the physical
basis for life

00:44:33.860 --> 00:44:37.280
with the intention turning
successively to protoplasm,

00:44:37.280 --> 00:44:40.570
the protein enzyme, the
virus, the gene and the cell.

00:44:40.570 --> 00:44:46.310
And by 1937 already the British
biologist Norman Pirie was arguing

00:44:46.310 --> 00:44:50.220
that the terms life and
living were really meaningless

00:44:50.220 --> 00:44:53.570
that he transition from
nonliving to living was comparable

00:44:53.570 --> 00:44:57.200 position:56%
to the gradual transition from
green to yellow in the spectrum it's

00:44:57.200 --> 00:45:01.030
like seeing a rainbow, you know,
when do you transition from one

00:45:01.030 --> 00:45:07.310 position:56%
to the other or like going from
acid to alkaline in chemistry except

00:45:07.310 --> 00:45:08.990
that life itself could
not be defined

00:45:08.990 --> 00:45:11.850
in terms of only one variable.

00:45:11.850 --> 00:45:15.000
Well, today the debate about the
origins of life is at the level

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:17.320
of the molecular assembly of life.

00:45:17.320 --> 00:45:19.880
We often see this NASA
definition of life

00:45:19.880 --> 00:45:24.770 position:56%
as a self-sustaining chemical system
capable of Darwinian evolution.

00:45:24.770 --> 00:45:27.440
But I think there's a consensus
that no single definition

00:45:27.440 --> 00:45:31.050
of life is totally satisfactory,
some philosophers and scientist

00:45:31.050 --> 00:45:34.520
like Carol Cleland
and Chris Chyba say

00:45:34.520 --> 00:45:39.100
that they've argued repeatedly
beginning with a series of papers

00:45:39.100 --> 00:45:43.810
in 2002 that all attempts to define
life were fundamentally misguided

00:45:43.810 --> 00:45:48.110
in the absence of a general living,
general theory of living systems

00:45:48.110 --> 00:45:50.900
which of course we don't have.

00:45:50.900 --> 00:45:55.600
Other philosopher such as Kelly
Smith call this stance the

00:45:55.600 --> 00:45:59.230
definition of pessimism and
argue that you don't need

00:45:59.230 --> 00:46:02.420
to have a universal definition of
life to have a working definition

00:46:02.420 --> 00:46:03.720
for any given circumstance.

00:46:03.720 --> 00:46:07.420
In other words, there has to
be a balance between definition

00:46:07.420 --> 00:46:09.280
of pessimism and pragmatism.

00:46:09.280 --> 00:46:12.560
And I really tend to
come down on that side

00:46:12.560 --> 00:46:16.000
on Kelly Smith's side
for several reasons.

00:46:16.000 --> 00:46:19.170
First of all, because we
really can't help ourselves

00:46:19.170 --> 00:46:20.910
from defining life, can we?

00:46:20.910 --> 00:46:24.700
Just as we can't help ourselves
from defining a lot of other things

00:46:24.700 --> 00:46:29.970
like say planet to take a
random example from astronomy.

00:46:29.970 --> 00:46:32.570
Secondly, institutions like NASA

00:46:32.570 --> 00:46:35.630
of course need an operational
definition of life

00:46:35.630 --> 00:46:37.210
if they're going to search for it.

00:46:37.210 --> 00:46:41.460
The latest astrobiology strategy
document specifically says the

00:46:41.460 --> 00:46:45.490
definitions of life and
function and evidence all--

00:46:45.490 --> 00:46:47.540
those kinds of things
shape our research

00:46:47.540 --> 00:46:51.020
and therefore we need them even
though we don't need to obsess

00:46:51.020 --> 00:46:52.430
over them and they
need to be elastic.

00:46:52.430 --> 00:46:56.850
We need to be able to adjust them.

00:46:56.850 --> 00:46:58.150
In astronomy, we think

00:46:58.150 --> 00:47:05.040
of the controversy surrounding
the question, is Pluto a planet?

00:47:05.040 --> 00:47:09.790 position:56%
You've seen the amazing images
coming from the New Horizons mission

00:47:09.790 --> 00:47:12.470
which David is also
writing a book about.

00:47:12.470 --> 00:47:17.220
But of course whether or not
Pluto is a planet depends

00:47:17.220 --> 00:47:18.520
on your definition.

00:47:18.520 --> 00:47:25.510
And the International Astronomical
Union 10 years ago last month

00:47:25.510 --> 00:47:29.360
decided that the answer was no
that Pluto was not a planet based

00:47:29.360 --> 00:47:31.420
on a rather arbitrary set

00:47:31.420 --> 00:47:33.100
of conditions I think
some people would say.

00:47:33.100 --> 00:47:36.370
It was a compromise among
the astronomic communities

00:47:36.370 --> 00:47:40.070
that define Pluto as a dwarf
planet and then declared

00:47:40.070 --> 00:47:42.750
that a dwarf planet
was not a planet.

00:47:42.750 --> 00:47:45.730
Well I voted for the dwarf planet
part but I've always thought

00:47:45.730 --> 00:47:48.240
that dwarf planet should
be a class of planet,

00:47:48.240 --> 00:47:51.120
but it's not by definition.

00:47:51.120 --> 00:47:56.450
So, the point is though
that it was defined in a way

00:47:56.450 --> 00:47:59.970 position:56%
that reflected these different
astronomical communities even though

00:47:59.970 --> 00:48:04.640
it disappointed some scientist
like Alan Stern who's the PI

00:48:04.640 --> 00:48:07.680
from the New Horizons
mission, not to mention a lot

00:48:07.680 --> 00:48:09.520
of other school kid
who were disappointed.

00:48:09.520 --> 00:48:12.320
It was-- an interesting
cultural phenomenon really.

00:48:12.320 --> 00:48:17.490
But you'll notice that
arguments over definition

00:48:17.490 --> 00:48:19.300 position:56%
of a planet didn't keep New Horizons

00:48:19.300 --> 00:48:22.330
from having a spectacular
mission, right?

00:48:22.330 --> 00:48:25.900
Alan likes to point out that Pluto
doesn't care if it's a planet

00:48:25.900 --> 00:48:28.520
or a dwarf planet so we could
go on and study it anyway.

00:48:28.520 --> 00:48:32.200
And the same is true of
the definition of problems

00:48:32.200 --> 00:48:33.880
with things like species.

00:48:33.880 --> 00:48:38.570
A common definition of species
is organisms that can interbreed,

00:48:38.570 --> 00:48:40.750
belong to the same species.

00:48:40.750 --> 00:48:44.400
Well we now know that Homo sapiens
and Neanderthal interbreed, right?

00:48:44.400 --> 00:48:47.540
So, most of us are
1 to 3% Neanderthal.

00:48:47.540 --> 00:48:51.830
So instead of throwing out the
concept of species we expand

00:48:51.830 --> 00:48:53.570
or adjust the definition.

00:48:53.570 --> 00:48:55.550
And the same isn't true--

00:48:55.550 --> 00:48:58.460
is also true of intelligence
David mentioned intelligence

00:48:58.460 --> 00:49:01.530
which a study people like to
scurred by talking about the search

00:49:01.530 --> 00:49:03.580
for extraterrestrial technology,

00:49:03.580 --> 00:49:06.090
not intelligence then they don't
have to define intelligence.

00:49:06.090 --> 00:49:07.670
And I remember right
here at the Library

00:49:07.670 --> 00:49:10.670
of Congress a few years ago
asking the philosopher John Searle

00:49:10.670 --> 00:49:14.340
about the concept of intelligence.

00:49:14.340 --> 00:49:15.730
He said, "Forget intelligence.

00:49:15.730 --> 00:49:18.240
The big question is consciousness."

00:49:18.240 --> 00:49:21.670
And of course nobody knows how to
define consciousness either, right?

00:49:21.670 --> 00:49:24.820
There's no consensus definition.

00:49:24.820 --> 00:49:27.550
So, we all settle for
operational definitions that apply

00:49:27.550 --> 00:49:28.960
to the specific task at hand.

00:49:28.960 --> 00:49:30.670
So, people like Carol Cleland

00:49:30.670 --> 00:49:35.020 position:56%
and philosophers I think have a good
point when they say that, you know,

00:49:35.020 --> 00:49:37.600
we can't have a universal
definition of life in the absence

00:49:37.600 --> 00:49:39.080
of living systems theory.

00:49:39.080 --> 00:49:43.260
I certainly agree with that but we
do need operational definitions.

00:49:43.260 --> 00:49:46.620
Now of course those operational
definitions can get you into a lot

00:49:46.620 --> 00:49:49.140
of trouble especially if you
choose the wrong definition

00:49:49.140 --> 00:49:53.430
when you go off searching for say
life of Mars and that was the case

00:49:53.430 --> 00:49:58.570 position:56%
with the Viking biology experiments,
all of which relied on a definition

00:49:58.570 --> 00:50:00.040
of life based on metabolism.

00:50:00.040 --> 00:50:05.360
Gil Levin, one of the principal
investigators still believe

00:50:05.360 --> 00:50:08.300
that he fond life on Mars,
claim that's no longer

00:50:08.300 --> 00:50:12.320
so much completely dismissed as it
used to be given what we now know

00:50:12.320 --> 00:50:15.140 position:56%
about the surface chemistry of Mars.

00:50:15.140 --> 00:50:18.320
For many years that result was
trumped by what's called the GC/MS,

00:50:18.320 --> 00:50:21.280
the Gas Chromatograph Mass
Spectrometer experiment

00:50:21.280 --> 00:50:24.740
because it show that there were
no organic molecules on Mars

00:50:24.740 --> 00:50:28.380
at those two landing sites
where the Viking Landers landed.

00:50:28.380 --> 00:50:31.010 position:56%
So, if you have no organic molecules
you can't have life, right?

00:50:31.010 --> 00:50:34.010
So that sort of wipes out all
the experiments on metabolism

00:50:34.010 --> 00:50:35.980 position:56%
and in fact a biochemical definition

00:50:35.980 --> 00:50:40.800 position:56%
of life trumped all the other
metabolic experiments until we found

00:50:40.800 --> 00:50:44.620 position:56%
out more about the role of
perchlorates on the surface of Mars.

00:50:44.620 --> 00:50:50.760
So the lesson of Viking seems to be
that experiments should be designed

00:50:50.760 --> 00:50:54.910
with multiple definitions
of life in mind.

00:50:54.910 --> 00:50:56.970
Now the best way to define
life of course would be

00:50:56.970 --> 00:51:01.290
to actually find some on
Mars or your [inaudible] some

00:51:01.290 --> 00:51:03.810
of these other places
and compare it to Earth.

00:51:03.810 --> 00:51:07.720
In that case if it was
truly a second genesis,

00:51:07.720 --> 00:51:11.150
we might have the beginnings
of a universal biology similar

00:51:11.150 --> 00:51:14.050
to a universal physics
that we think we have now.

00:51:14.050 --> 00:51:17.270
And that's the second issue I
want to address the aspirations

00:51:17.270 --> 00:51:20.490
for universality by
which I mean two things.

00:51:20.490 --> 00:51:22.420
Is there a universal biology

00:51:22.420 --> 00:51:27.440
as there is a universal
physics, and is life universal?

00:51:27.440 --> 00:51:30.380
In other words, is it spread
throughout the universe?

00:51:30.380 --> 00:51:32.440
So in this respect I
think there's no doubt

00:51:32.440 --> 00:51:36.330
that the space program
really catalyzed aspirations

00:51:36.330 --> 00:51:38.900
for universality in
both of these ways.

00:51:38.900 --> 00:51:44.140
Implicitly or explicitly those
at the intersection of exobiology

00:51:44.140 --> 00:51:48.670
and origins of life expressed
interest in the desire

00:51:48.670 --> 00:51:51.050
for a universal biology, one

00:51:51.050 --> 00:51:54.970
that might be a more general
than terrestrial life.

00:51:54.970 --> 00:52:00.070
In the Soviet Union, Oparin
called exobiology and the origins

00:52:00.070 --> 00:52:03.100
of life the inseparable connection.

00:52:03.100 --> 00:52:06.430
And Stanley Miller
did the same thing.

00:52:06.430 --> 00:52:10.210
And here we saw the Urey-Miller
experiment this morning.

00:52:10.210 --> 00:52:13.400
Some of you may notice that I have
1952 whereas I forget who it was

00:52:13.400 --> 00:52:17.250
who showed it this
morning, had 1953.

00:52:17.250 --> 00:52:20.770
I think that's the difference
and this is an interesting thing

00:52:20.770 --> 00:52:24.270
about when is the discover made, is
it made when the experiment is done

00:52:24.270 --> 00:52:27.130
or is it made when the
publication comes out?

00:52:27.130 --> 00:52:30.760 position:56%
Well in this case the experiment was
done in '52 but it's always cited

00:52:30.760 --> 00:52:33.030
as '53 because that's
when the public--

00:52:33.030 --> 00:52:34.560
that's an interesting thing

00:52:34.560 --> 00:52:38.950
in science I've done
a whole book on that.

00:52:38.950 --> 00:52:43.670
Anyway, both of these scientists
said that exobiology and origins

00:52:43.670 --> 00:52:47.850
of life are the inseparable
connection.

00:52:47.850 --> 00:52:52.180
Origins of life studies
quickly became a central focus

00:52:52.180 --> 00:52:56.410
of exobiology bringing
into the field scientist

00:52:56.410 --> 00:52:59.270
such as Melvin Calvin.

00:52:59.270 --> 00:53:04.590
Once interviewed Melvin Calvin in
his office at Berkeley best known

00:53:04.590 --> 00:53:09.870
for his Nobel Prize and it
happen to do with photosynthesis.

00:53:09.870 --> 00:53:13.340
But Calvin said in his
mind there was no question

00:53:13.340 --> 00:53:17.250
about the Darwinian behavior of
molecules and if that were true,

00:53:17.250 --> 00:53:21.380
that meant it must be true
in the entire universe.

00:53:21.380 --> 00:53:24.800
His student Cyril Ponnamperuma
said basically the same thing.

00:53:24.800 --> 00:53:29.600
If we can understand how it
began here we'll know something

00:53:29.600 --> 00:53:33.900
about how it began and if it began
out there and if it's repeated

00:53:33.900 --> 00:53:35.920
in a staggering number
of planetary systems

00:53:35.920 --> 00:53:41.470
in our galaxy, or in
our universe even.

00:53:41.470 --> 00:53:44.640
Now that was written in 1972

00:53:44.640 --> 00:53:47.420
when there were no other
solar systems known aside

00:53:47.420 --> 00:53:48.950
from our own, right?

00:53:48.950 --> 00:53:51.210
Of course now we know
that they're everywhere.

00:53:51.210 --> 00:53:53.860
So in short this space program--

00:53:53.860 --> 00:53:57.430
my point is the space program
catalyzed the integration of origin

00:53:57.430 --> 00:54:01.730
of life and extraterrestrial life
studies as theories and experiments

00:54:01.730 --> 00:54:04.680
that were previously viewed just
in the context of life beginning

00:54:04.680 --> 00:54:07.030
on Earth were increasingly seen

00:54:07.030 --> 00:54:11.190
in extraterrestrial context
integrating these two fields

00:54:11.190 --> 00:54:13.140
of study.

00:54:13.140 --> 00:54:17.120
Now, these conclusions
about universality

00:54:17.120 --> 00:54:20.610
of really hide a deep
metaphysical preconception

00:54:20.610 --> 00:54:25.990 position:56%
and that is the question of chance
and necessity in the origin of life.

00:54:25.990 --> 00:54:29.750
I think it's a real tribute
to the scientist involved

00:54:29.750 --> 00:54:32.290
that they recognize
their preconceptions.

00:54:32.290 --> 00:54:36.680 position:56%
In fact, the philosophical question
that dominated the problem of origin

00:54:36.680 --> 00:54:40.850
of life beyond Earth was exactly
that, what was the role of chance

00:54:40.850 --> 00:54:43.390
and necessity in the
formation of life?

00:54:43.390 --> 00:54:47.050
After all that question hinge the
whole enterprise of exobiology,

00:54:47.050 --> 00:54:49.300
what we now call astrobiology,

00:54:49.300 --> 00:54:52.940
because if life was just a chance
occurrence and was very rare then,

00:54:52.940 --> 00:54:57.150 position:56%
you know, it might never happen
again no matter how big the universe

00:54:57.150 --> 00:54:59.930
was or how much time you had.

00:54:59.930 --> 00:55:03.360
In my mind the two prototypes
for the debate over chance

00:55:03.360 --> 00:55:08.000
and necessity are Jacques
Monod and Christian de Duve

00:55:08.000 --> 00:55:11.740
of here you see Jacques
Monod a French biologist.

00:55:11.740 --> 00:55:16.340
Monod and de Duve both
are Nobel Prize winners.

00:55:16.340 --> 00:55:19.630
Monod was awarded the
Nobel Price in 1965

00:55:19.630 --> 00:55:21.870
for explaining the
genetic regulation

00:55:21.870 --> 00:55:23.760
of protein synthesis in cells.

00:55:23.760 --> 00:55:27.340
And he drew on the latest
results on molecular biology

00:55:27.340 --> 00:55:30.420
to illustrate how chance
predominated

00:55:30.420 --> 00:55:32.940
in all aspects of life's
development.

00:55:32.940 --> 00:55:35.860
And he wrote a classic
volume called "Chance

00:55:35.860 --> 00:55:39.310
and Necessity" written in 1971.

00:55:39.310 --> 00:55:41.740
And he wrote this--
famously wrote this phrase

00:55:41.740 --> 00:55:44.600 position:56%
which you often see quoted, the
universe was not pregnant with life,

00:55:44.600 --> 00:55:46.180
nor the biosphere with man.

00:55:46.180 --> 00:55:48.780
Our number just came up
in a Monte Carlo game.

00:55:48.780 --> 00:55:53.030
So, he came to that view because
of what he called the revelation

00:55:53.030 --> 00:55:57.470
and the disappointment that the
sequences composing the insulin

00:55:57.470 --> 00:56:00.200
protein showed no general
law of assembly,

00:56:00.200 --> 00:56:02.450
only the blind workings of chance.

00:56:02.450 --> 00:56:05.700
Many scientists since
that time have agreed

00:56:05.700 --> 00:56:10.820
with him including some astronomers
like Fred Hoyle who famously argued

00:56:10.820 --> 00:56:14.380
that the origin of life by
chance was about as likely

00:56:14.380 --> 00:56:20.650
as a 747 aircraft being assembled
spontaneously from a junkyard,

00:56:20.650 --> 00:56:22.690
pretty, pretty good image.

00:56:22.690 --> 00:56:24.900
He thought it was vastly
more probably

00:56:24.900 --> 00:56:28.650
that life had been assembled
by a cosmic intelligence.

00:56:28.650 --> 00:56:32.280
But before the religious people
could get to excited he emphasize

00:56:32.280 --> 00:56:35.510
in his opinion it was not a
supernatural intelligence,

00:56:35.510 --> 00:56:37.980
but that's another subject.

00:56:37.980 --> 00:56:41.950
And in his book "Advocating
Panspermia" of Francis Crick tended

00:56:41.950 --> 00:56:45.420
to agree that life could not have
risen by chance here on Earth.

00:56:45.420 --> 00:56:50.440
Well, a quarter century after
that, here's Christian de Duve,

00:56:50.440 --> 00:56:55.830
who just died last year, wrote
a book called "Vital Dust,

00:56:55.830 --> 00:56:57.670
Life as a Cosmic Imperative".

00:56:57.670 --> 00:57:00.680
And he argued just the opposite

00:57:00.680 --> 00:57:06.860
from his Nobel Prize
French colleague Monod.

00:57:06.860 --> 00:57:11.790
And he's a very well-known
biochemist also best known

00:57:11.790 --> 00:57:14.250
for his discoveries related
to the structure and function

00:57:14.250 --> 00:57:17.770
of organization of a cell.

00:57:17.770 --> 00:57:21.670
And he was most impressed with
the organic molecules then being

00:57:21.670 --> 00:57:23.030
discovered in space.

00:57:23.030 --> 00:57:26.190
So it's interesting how these
two came through their ideas

00:57:26.190 --> 00:57:28.710
about chance and necessity.

00:57:28.710 --> 00:57:32.230
It was based on things that were
currently happening sometimes

00:57:32.230 --> 00:57:34.650
on their own research.

00:57:34.650 --> 00:57:38.690
So he wrote, as you see here,
done in the organic cloud

00:57:38.690 --> 00:57:43.500
and here he's talking about these
organic molecules being discovered

00:57:43.500 --> 00:57:45.830 position:56%
in space which we now know exist all

00:57:45.830 --> 00:57:51.650
over in interstellar molecular
clouds that they were everywhere

00:57:51.650 --> 00:57:54.070
and the conclusion
seem to him inescapable

00:57:54.070 --> 00:57:56.920
that where the conditions are
similar to those that prevail

00:57:56.920 --> 00:57:59.600
on our planet that
there would be life.

00:57:59.600 --> 00:58:01.750
And he went so far as to
say that those who claim

00:58:01.750 --> 00:58:05.340
that it's highly improbable
just have a look closely enough

00:58:05.340 --> 00:58:06.640
at the chemical realities.

00:58:06.640 --> 00:58:07.940
So there you have two, you know,

00:58:07.940 --> 00:58:10.270
pretty smart guys both
a Nobel Prize winners

00:58:10.270 --> 00:58:14.650
with totally different
points of view on that.

00:58:14.650 --> 00:58:23.560
OK. I think it's one of
the hallmarks of exobiology

00:58:23.560 --> 00:58:27.250
and now astrobiology that is
practitioners place their faith

00:58:27.250 --> 00:58:31.730
in more in necessity than in chance
or at least a high probability

00:58:31.730 --> 00:58:33.640
of the origin of life
under proper conditions.

00:58:33.640 --> 00:58:38.340
It was their most basic
metaphysical presupposition.

00:58:38.340 --> 00:58:41.260 position:56%
Otherwise, they wouldn't waste their
time searching for like, right?

00:58:41.260 --> 00:58:42.810
If you don't think it's
very likely you're not going

00:58:42.810 --> 00:58:45.290
to put much time into it.

00:58:45.290 --> 00:58:48.650
I happen to agree that this
is a good supposition--

00:58:48.650 --> 00:58:52.180
presupposition partly because
