01:52:46.220 --> 01:52:49.990 position:56%
Mostly because like animals showed
up and just ruined the neighborhood.

01:52:49.990 --> 01:52:51.620
I mean, they're used
to be much more common.

01:52:51.620 --> 01:52:52.920
And so actually you have to go--

01:52:52.920 --> 01:52:55.190
you have to look harder for
stromatolites than you used to.

01:52:55.190 --> 01:52:56.490
But, you know, it--

01:52:56.490 --> 01:53:00.690 position:56%
&gt;&gt; It doesn't strike to as a
meaningful that stromatolite happens

01:53:00.690 --> 01:53:04.490
to be very first form of life--

01:53:04.490 --> 01:53:06.040
&gt;&gt; Carl Zimmer: No, it's not
the very first form of life.

01:53:06.040 --> 01:53:08.650
It's the oldest form of
life that we have found.

01:53:08.650 --> 01:53:13.470
And, you know, and that does
speak to the fact that there had

01:53:13.470 --> 01:53:17.170
to be hundred of millions of years
of evolution to get to that point

01:53:17.170 --> 01:53:21.160
of cell-- those are presumably
cells, DNA, and protein in them

01:53:21.160 --> 01:53:22.900
and that-- and with communities

01:53:22.900 --> 01:53:25.800
of different species
interacting, cooperating.

01:53:25.800 --> 01:53:27.450
Yeah, that's no small feat.

01:53:27.450 --> 01:53:30.220
But, you know, it was-- there
could've been hundreds of millions

01:53:30.220 --> 01:53:32.220
of years of evolution
leading up to that point.

01:53:32.220 --> 01:53:36.650
This is just the oldest sign of
life that people have found so far,

01:53:36.650 --> 01:53:39.040
3.7 billion years ago,
the Earth had been

01:53:39.040 --> 01:53:41.680
around for 800 million
years already, so.

01:53:41.680 --> 01:53:42.980
&gt;&gt; David Grinspoon:
And when we say--

01:53:42.980 --> 01:53:45.480
when you say the earliest form
of life, I mean, there's a truth

01:53:45.480 --> 01:53:49.640 position:56%
to that but it's different from like
finding a giraffe that's 3.7 billion

01:53:49.640 --> 01:53:50.970
years old and saying,
"Oh, wow, those are--

01:53:50.970 --> 01:53:52.520
that's a long standing
form of life."

01:53:52.520 --> 01:53:56.980
Because the stromatolite is not
an organism, it's a microbial mat.

01:53:56.980 --> 01:54:03.620
It's a way of a community of
microbes deciding to live together

01:54:03.620 --> 01:54:07.280 position:56%
in sort of a horizontal arrangement.

01:54:07.280 --> 01:54:11.360
So, there's, potentially,
an argument from biophysics

01:54:11.360 --> 01:54:13.010 position:56%
for as kind of universality of that.

01:54:13.010 --> 01:54:15.890
In fact, people talk about
looking for stromatolites on Mars.

01:54:15.890 --> 01:54:17.530
Actually, maybe that's a stretch.

01:54:17.530 --> 01:54:20.270
But it's less of a stretch in
talking about looking for a giraffe

01:54:20.270 --> 01:54:24.980
on Mars because there's sort of a
basic almost physics or, you know,

01:54:24.980 --> 01:54:29.350
basic sort of geometry to why a
simple life might arrange itself

01:54:29.350 --> 01:54:30.650
in that way on a planet.

01:54:30.650 --> 01:54:37.540
&gt;&gt; Which is not a preserved
life form, it's just a bunch

01:54:37.540 --> 01:54:41.710
of physical way in which
microbial that's formed.

01:54:41.710 --> 01:54:45.240
&gt;&gt; David Grinspoon:
It's an architecture.

01:54:45.240 --> 01:54:46.540
&gt;&gt; Nathaniel Comfort: Yeah.

01:54:46.540 --> 01:54:47.840
&gt;&gt; That's a very nice picture.

01:54:47.840 --> 01:54:50.420
&gt;&gt; Steven Benner: Well, I want to
encourage your sense of skepticism.

01:54:50.420 --> 01:54:55.620
Because I passed the stromatolite
around and I got it back

01:54:55.620 --> 01:54:59.330
and nobody remarked me and says,

01:54:59.330 --> 01:55:03.280
"What the hell do you think you're
doing trying to tell me this is

01:55:03.280 --> 01:55:07.100
as a remnant of a life form?

01:55:07.100 --> 01:55:13.290
But it is a rock and it's a rock
with precipitated material in it."

01:55:13.290 --> 01:55:18.380
So what's you're observing here
is the precipitated inorganic,

01:55:18.380 --> 01:55:20.210
insoluble material.

01:55:20.210 --> 01:55:24.400
And we want to encourage
you to ask the question

01:55:24.400 --> 01:55:29.940
when you encounter somebody like
me saying as you [inaudible],

01:55:29.940 --> 01:55:33.350
how could you possibly know that?

01:55:33.350 --> 01:55:34.760
Now, they know it, right?

01:55:34.760 --> 01:55:38.250
There's a lot of work
that goes in that,

01:55:38.250 --> 01:55:40.610
and many, many PhD dissertations.

01:55:40.610 --> 01:55:43.830
But, yeah, I mean that's a
good sentiment to have, right?

01:55:43.830 --> 01:55:46.990
When someone tells you
[inaudible], for example,

01:55:46.990 --> 01:55:52.000
how do you know whether
it's 3.7 billion years?

01:55:52.000 --> 01:55:57.500
And the answer is, well, there's
an answer to that question.

01:55:57.500 --> 01:56:00.470
I think it was actually
on the paper.

01:56:00.470 --> 01:56:04.760
But, yeah, these are the kinds
of questions that you should ask.

01:56:04.760 --> 01:56:06.930
And, of course, that's where the--

01:56:06.930 --> 01:56:12.700
we try to train the students
to go deeper so that we can--

01:56:12.700 --> 01:56:16.530
we'd love asking PhD
candidates, you know, yeah,

01:56:16.530 --> 01:56:17.830
do you think water is H2O?

01:56:17.830 --> 01:56:20.330
What's the primary
data that say that--

01:56:20.330 --> 01:56:23.630
what are the primary data
that say that water is H2O?

01:56:23.630 --> 01:56:25.310 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Carl Zimmer: And those-- And
there are some "fossils" from almost

01:56:25.310 --> 01:56:28.750
that old that people don't
think are fossils anymore,

01:56:28.750 --> 01:56:30.780
that they were just-- they
looked a lot a like them.

01:56:30.780 --> 01:56:32.430
It gets very tricky with things
like microbial mats that old.

01:56:32.430 --> 01:56:33.730
It gets really hard to
figure out what's living

01:56:33.730 --> 01:56:35.160
and what just this rocks that
look like what you'd expect.

01:56:35.160 --> 01:56:36.460
But, yeah, it seems like
this new one, I don't know,

01:56:36.460 --> 01:56:37.890
people seemed to be pretty solid
on it although-- You think so?

01:56:37.890 --> 01:56:39.190
All right, he thinks so.

01:56:39.190 --> 01:56:40.490
&gt;&gt; David Grinspoon: I don't know.

01:56:40.490 --> 01:56:41.790
No. Don't listen to me.

01:56:41.790 --> 01:56:43.090
I don't know.

01:56:43.090 --> 01:56:44.390
I mean--

01:56:44.390 --> 01:56:45.690 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Carl Zimmer: If I had written
the article I would have called you.

01:56:45.690 --> 01:56:46.990
&gt;&gt; David Grinspoon: If you go
over the Smithsonian today and go

01:56:46.990 --> 01:56:48.290
into National History Museum,
you still see those shops--

01:56:48.290 --> 01:56:49.590
carbon specs, which we thought
used to be cyanobacteria

01:56:49.590 --> 01:56:50.890
which we don't think are there.

01:56:50.890 --> 01:56:52.190
They're still in the
Smithsonian as example of life.

01:56:52.190 --> 01:56:53.490
&gt;&gt; Nathaniel Comfort: Yeah, yeah.

01:56:53.490 --> 01:56:54.790
OK.

01:56:54.790 --> 01:56:56.090
&gt;&gt; Steven Benner: Right
by that big elephant.

01:56:56.090 --> 01:56:57.390
&gt;&gt; Nathaniel Comfort: Yes.

01:56:57.390 --> 01:56:58.690
&gt;&gt; Hi there.

01:56:58.690 --> 01:56:59.990
I'm with the Richard
Dawkins Foundation

01:56:59.990 --> 01:57:01.290
and the Center for Inquiry.

01:57:01.290 --> 01:57:02.590
My question is to you, scientists
and science communicators,

01:57:02.590 --> 01:57:03.890
you still have to operate
within a political environment,

01:57:03.890 --> 01:57:05.190
and it determines what
resources you have,

01:57:05.190 --> 01:57:06.490
it determines whether you
have freedom of inquiry.

01:57:06.490 --> 01:57:07.790
So I'm asking you, what
is the current status

01:57:07.790 --> 01:57:09.090
of the political environment
in which you operate?

01:57:09.090 --> 01:57:10.390
And are there any danger signs

01:57:10.390 --> 01:57:11.690
that you're concerned
about down the road?

01:57:11.690 --> 01:57:12.990
[ Laughter ]

01:57:12.990 --> 01:57:14.290
&gt;&gt; Nathaniel Comfort: Let's
keep this nonpartisan.

01:57:14.290 --> 01:57:15.590
Everybody is passing.

01:57:15.590 --> 01:57:16.890
&gt;&gt; David Grinspoon: I don't
know why people are handing me

01:57:16.890 --> 01:57:18.190
the microphone.

01:57:18.190 --> 01:57:19.490
[ Laughter ]

01:57:19.490 --> 01:57:20.790
I--

01:57:20.790 --> 01:57:22.090
&gt;&gt; You're not going to
have equal opportunities.

01:57:22.090 --> 01:57:23.390
&gt;&gt; David Grinspoon:
Yeah, that's right.

01:57:23.390 --> 01:57:24.830
Personally, I mean, I'm
hesitating because I don't feel

01:57:24.830 --> 01:57:26.520
like I have a really profound--

01:57:26.520 --> 01:57:28.500
I mean, it's an important
question you asked.

01:57:28.500 --> 01:57:33.270
With this particular area of
inquiry I don't feel a lot

01:57:33.270 --> 01:57:35.170
of political pressure.

01:57:35.170 --> 01:57:40.600 position:56%
I mean, out there in our society
there are the forces that, you know,

01:57:40.600 --> 01:57:45.200
want to teach-- you know, that are
concerned about teaching evolution

01:57:45.200 --> 01:57:47.870
in the schools and, you know, the
stuff that you guys at the Center

01:57:47.870 --> 01:57:49.380
for Inquiry are very well aware of.

01:57:49.380 --> 01:57:52.750
And, you know, those are things
we're aware of but they're not--

01:57:52.750 --> 01:57:54.730
you know, it's not affecting
our ability right now

01:57:54.730 --> 01:57:57.300
to do the research we do.

01:57:57.300 --> 01:58:02.310
It's certainly, you know, affecting
our ability to, in a larger sense,

01:58:02.310 --> 01:58:07.420
communicate and have a
science literate society,

01:58:07.420 --> 01:58:09.110
which is a wider concern.

01:58:09.110 --> 01:58:13.500 position:56%
And, of course, you know, in my
area of astrobiology which has to do

01:58:13.500 --> 01:58:19.480
with climate modeling, I'm,
you know, working with people

01:58:19.480 --> 01:58:23.720
who are feeling the effects of
some of the slight, you know,

01:58:23.720 --> 01:58:28.120
inquisition like aspects
of some corners

01:58:28.120 --> 01:58:31.380
of our government's approach
to climate [inaudible].

01:58:31.380 --> 01:58:35.040
And so, you know, there
are some danger signs

01:58:35.040 --> 01:58:37.950
on the dashboard, some
lights flashing.

01:58:37.950 --> 01:58:40.880
But, you know, as far as
there's nobody telling us not

01:58:40.880 --> 01:58:45.470
to research the origin of life or
anything like that, there's no sort

01:58:45.470 --> 01:58:48.450
of acute political constraint
on this area of inquiry.

01:58:48.450 --> 01:58:51.950
But I think you know as
members of a society at large,

01:58:51.950 --> 01:58:53.750
the concern of science
and education,

01:58:53.750 --> 01:58:56.510
there are certainly some things
we need to pay attention to.

01:58:56.510 --> 01:58:59.560
&gt;&gt; Steven Benner: Can I turn
the question back to you?

01:58:59.560 --> 01:59:01.660
Although you seem to
have disappeared, what--

01:59:01.660 --> 01:59:04.870
I mean you work at something with
the Richard Dawkins in the name.

01:59:04.870 --> 01:59:08.010
So, what is your experience?

01:59:08.010 --> 01:59:12.370
&gt;&gt; Well, I run the Richard Dawkins
Foundation for Reason and Science.

01:59:12.370 --> 01:59:17.320
And we promote atheism
and scientific literacy.

01:59:17.320 --> 01:59:18.950
&gt;&gt; Steven Benner: So you
have a more direct contact

01:59:18.950 --> 01:59:20.950
to the public than--
I mean, I talk--

01:59:20.950 --> 01:59:22.250
&gt;&gt; And, you know, we--

01:59:22.250 --> 01:59:24.090
&gt;&gt; Steven Benner: -- Richmond
society I talk creations all the

01:59:24.090 --> 01:59:27.490
time, but you have a more
closer contact to this.

01:59:27.490 --> 01:59:28.790
And what's your experience?

01:59:28.790 --> 01:59:33.560
&gt;&gt; Well, I work in a realm where
I'm trying to debunk mythologies.

01:59:33.560 --> 01:59:38.440
And people cling to those
ideas and are very hostile

01:59:38.440 --> 01:59:40.820
to anyone who challenges them.

01:59:40.820 --> 01:59:43.270
I would say when you're
dealing with pure science,

01:59:43.270 --> 01:59:50.870
it's easier to put forth ideas
often-- to be perfectly frank,

01:59:50.870 --> 01:59:55.670
they're a little over the head of
most average people, laypeople.

01:59:55.670 --> 02:00:00.040
So, they're not going to be
challenging you directly.

02:00:00.040 --> 02:00:03.480
But we run a program, for
instance, the Teacher Institute

02:00:03.480 --> 02:00:04.860
for Evolutionary Science School,

02:00:04.860 --> 02:00:09.490
where we teach middle school
teachers how to teach evolution.

02:00:09.490 --> 02:00:14.950
And we receive, on a daily
basis, responses from teachers

02:00:14.950 --> 02:00:17.860
that say they can't
teach the subject.

02:00:17.860 --> 02:00:23.530
The kids will turn their chair
to the wall rather than listen

02:00:23.530 --> 02:00:27.360 position:56%
to something that defies what
they've been taught by their pastor,

02:00:27.360 --> 02:00:32.270
their priest, their minister,
their imam, the rabbi.

02:00:32.270 --> 02:00:33.670
&gt;&gt; Steven Benner: Would
you say that's increasing?

02:00:33.670 --> 02:00:34.970
Decreasing?

02:00:34.970 --> 02:00:36.770
Do you have any reason
to make a statement?

02:00:36.770 --> 02:00:38.870
&gt;&gt; Well, I don't know.

02:00:38.870 --> 02:00:41.450
I mean, I do know that
43% of Americans say

02:00:41.450 --> 02:00:43.750
that human beings arrived
on this Earth fully formed

02:00:43.750 --> 02:00:46.390
within the last 10,000 years.

02:00:46.390 --> 02:00:47.900
&gt;&gt; Steven Benner: Because
I talk a lot

02:00:47.900 --> 02:00:50.250
to the Gainesville
creationist community.

02:00:50.250 --> 02:00:53.430
I just gave a talk, you know,
what religion is that science--

02:00:53.430 --> 02:00:55.850
what science is that
religion is not.

02:00:55.850 --> 02:01:00.850
The subtitle for that talk is, "Why
scientist do so very little of it?"

02:01:00.850 --> 02:01:03.490
But the bottom line is
that they're nice people.

02:01:03.490 --> 02:01:08.080
They don't seem to be--
not in kind of hostility.

02:01:08.080 --> 02:01:09.380
They-- Of course, the public,

02:01:09.380 --> 02:01:12.220
even the creationists very
much values the technology.

02:01:12.220 --> 02:01:15.240
The new medicines, the new,
you know, therapies and stuff

02:01:15.240 --> 02:01:18.290
that is coming from
science as whatever that is.

02:01:18.290 --> 02:01:20.040
Many of them are more concerned

02:01:20.040 --> 02:01:22.530
about whether their daughter
is going to come home pregnant

02:01:22.530 --> 02:01:23.960
or they're going to be--
you know, they're worried

02:01:23.960 --> 02:01:26.310
about the social decay,
they're worried about all sorts

02:01:26.310 --> 02:01:28.530
of other things for
which origins of life,

02:01:28.530 --> 02:01:30.360
or evolution is a proxy, right?

02:01:30.360 --> 02:01:32.850
It doesn't really say
it's a sort of authority.

02:01:32.850 --> 02:01:34.210
They don't actually much care.

02:01:34.210 --> 02:01:37.600
There's no constructive reason
to care one way or other

02:01:37.600 --> 02:01:39.040
when the Earth was formed.

02:01:39.040 --> 02:01:41.580
I mean, how does that
influence their daily life,

02:01:41.580 --> 02:01:42.970
but it does influence
their daily life

02:01:42.970 --> 02:01:45.600
that their kid come home
drug addicted, for example,

02:01:45.600 --> 02:01:48.460
and they're worried about the
laws of authority that would tend

02:01:48.460 --> 02:01:51.140
to prevent drug addiction, at
least that's how they view it among

02:01:51.140 --> 02:01:52.440
their children.

02:01:52.440 --> 02:01:54.280
But-- So you actually think
that their-- I mean is it--

02:01:54.280 --> 02:01:56.870
&gt;&gt; I think there are direct
societal consequences to that kind

02:01:56.870 --> 02:01:59.650
of scientific illiteracy
in the general population.

02:01:59.650 --> 02:02:00.950
&gt;&gt; Steven Benner: Well,
I agree with that, but--

02:02:00.950 --> 02:02:03.740
&gt;&gt; And I think that there are
consequences for resources

02:02:03.740 --> 02:02:07.310
for science and public policy.

02:02:07.310 --> 02:02:11.690
From stem cell research, to,
you know, abortion rights,

02:02:11.690 --> 02:02:16.400
to same sex marriage,
to climate change.

02:02:16.400 --> 02:02:20.240
So-- And I wish scientists
would get a little more engaged

02:02:20.240 --> 02:02:24.190
in these battles, because
we need you.

02:02:24.190 --> 02:02:25.490
&gt;&gt; Nathaniel Comfort: OK.

02:02:25.490 --> 02:02:27.580
We have a couple of
repeat questions.

02:02:27.580 --> 02:02:30.470
I want to get to people who
haven't asked a question first

02:02:30.470 --> 02:02:32.830
and then we'll get to you.

02:02:32.830 --> 02:02:34.130
So, OK.

02:02:34.130 --> 02:02:38.430
&gt;&gt; OK. And that is, you know, we've
spoken about the origins of life

02:02:38.430 --> 02:02:42.740
and the difficulties
of defining life.

02:02:42.740 --> 02:02:45.290
And, you know, we talked
about DNA, RNA.

02:02:45.290 --> 02:02:51.290
But it seems to me that what we--

02:02:51.290 --> 02:02:54.220
at least what I think is
what's really interesting,

02:02:54.220 --> 02:02:57.500
the really interesting life
on Earth, the people all

02:02:57.500 --> 02:03:01.400
around us are-- is eukaryotic life.

02:03:01.400 --> 02:03:11.560
And can we imagine intelligent
life arising with life forms

02:03:11.560 --> 02:03:15.630
that have not experienced
a eukaryotic threshold?

02:03:15.630 --> 02:03:23.500
Is there some other path that
people have at least thought about?

02:03:23.500 --> 02:03:27.100
&gt;&gt; Nathaniel Comfort: Meaning is
a membrane-bound nucleus necessary

02:03:27.100 --> 02:03:28.720
for higher--

02:03:28.720 --> 02:03:32.810
&gt;&gt; For most interesting
multicellular life.

02:03:32.810 --> 02:03:34.130
&gt;&gt; Nathaniel Comfort:
For a development

02:03:34.130 --> 02:03:37.150
of a neural system or
something like that?

02:03:37.150 --> 02:03:40.280
&gt;&gt; Yes. Because, I mean,
you know, we're thinking

02:03:40.280 --> 02:03:42.740
about the first step
we've got microbes.

02:03:42.740 --> 02:03:44.660
Hurray, we've got microbes.

02:03:44.660 --> 02:03:47.670
Which is most of what
we've had on Earth.

02:03:47.670 --> 02:03:51.530
But the part that makes
our heart beat is

02:03:51.530 --> 02:03:55.190
when you start getting
eukaryotes and multicellular life

02:03:55.190 --> 02:03:59.940
and complex life with
tissues and organs.

02:03:59.940 --> 02:04:03.370
And I'm wondering, has
there been any thought given

02:04:03.370 --> 02:04:07.570
to how complex life with
tissues and organs and this sort

02:04:07.570 --> 02:04:12.020
of thing might have a reason in the
absence of a eukaryotic threshold?

02:04:12.020 --> 02:04:15.760
&gt;&gt; Nathaniel Comfort: Let me
throw in there just into the mix,

02:04:15.760 --> 02:04:22.970
whether that question really is
about the transition from one

02:04:22.970 --> 02:04:27.100
of the major forms of information
exchange being lateral gene

02:04:27.100 --> 02:04:31.590
transfer, shifting toward a
more vertical gene transfer

02:04:31.590 --> 02:04:34.890
and the invention of sex.

02:04:34.890 --> 02:04:38.650
Possibly another way of
phrasing the question.

02:04:38.650 --> 02:04:40.030
&gt;&gt; Matthew Schrenk: I just
also like to add that some

02:04:40.030 --> 02:04:42.660
of the things we talked about
recently, the stromatolites,

02:04:42.660 --> 02:04:46.100
the biofilms earlier today,
horizontal gene exchange,

02:04:46.100 --> 02:04:50.660
all these are-- perhaps they
don't immediately translate

02:04:50.660 --> 02:04:54.060
into intelligent life back and
send out signals to other planets.

02:04:54.060 --> 02:04:57.470
But these are the beginnings
of differentiation

02:04:57.470 --> 02:05:01.990
and these microbial communities are
working together at some skills,

02:05:01.990 --> 02:05:04.440
sensing the environment,
having feedbacks

02:05:04.440 --> 02:05:08.160
